From 930fc08d9f63b1c94c2ca82cf62a10c2146d70f4 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 25 Jun 2026 03:39:01 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 2/2] Address review findings in orchestration layer

Correctness / billing:
- Charge token usage on the orchestration path with the same conservative
  estimate fallback the direct path uses when a worker omits the usage block
  (closes a token-quota/limit bypass).
- Tier-B returns partial usage on a mid-DAG failure so already-consumed
  tokens are still charged.

Control plane / config:
- Reject virtual-model names that collide with a real model/alias/backend
  model (would silently shadow the real model via the Handles() early
  return); validate that every worker model is served by a backend.
- Worker dispatch honors the model-registry enabled kill-switch and the
  routing allow_degraded_backends flag (shared store.FilterRoutable).

Logic / governance:
- Conductor pairs verifier+synthesizer on one budget gate so the verifier is
  never run only to discard its critique; thinker fills budget==2.
- Clamp negative/out-of-range secret levels so the access list can't be
  bypassed.
- Per-call timeout honors a backend TimeoutMS larger than the global default
  (matches the direct path), not only smaller.

Observability:
- Emit ActiveRequests gauge for orchestrated requests and per-backend
  BackendErrors / Timeouts counters from worker calls.
- Status is checked before decoding so a non-JSON error page surfaces the
  real status; empty-choices responses are counted as backend errors.
- Slot acquisition retries on a lost race instead of hard-failing.
- Streaming responses carry usage and x_orchestration in the final chunk.

Cleanup:
- Share proxy.DefaultTransport and store.FilterRoutable; remove duplicate
  apiKeyLabelOf; parse the request body one fewer time (secret_level read
  from the handler's existing peek).

Tests: collision/reachability validation, verifier/synth pairing, partial
usage on failure, secret-level clamp, kill-switch, backend-timeout honoring,
omitted-usage contract, and a sample-config load test.

